uuel</i>, <i>Huwel</i>, <i>Huwal</i>, <i>Howael</i>, cognate with the Welsh name. Bretons were especially numerous in the eastern counties of England. See   Powell  .","English: perhaps from a Middle English personal name <i>Huwel</i> (spelled <i>Howel</i>), a shortening of <i>Huwelot</i> or <i>Huelin</i> (see   Hewlett   and   Huling  ), both pet forms of Middle English <i>Huw</i> (see   Hugh  ).","English: habitational name from Howell (Lincolnshire), from an uncertain initial element + Old English <i>wella</i> ‘well, spring, stream’."],"variants":[{"name":"Howle","meanings":["English and Welsh:","variant of   Howell  .","variant of   Hole  ."]},{"name":"Howells","meanings":["English and Welsh (Glamorgan): variant of   Howell  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent English <i>-s</i>.","English: perhaps occasionally a nickname for someone who was fearless, from Middle English <i>houe</i>, <i>houwe</i> ‘anxiety, fear’ (Old English <i>hogu</i> or <i>hoga</i>) + <i>les</i> ‘less’. If this has survived as a modern surname, its pronunciation has been influenced by that of the name in 1 above.","English: variant of   Holes  ."]},{"name":"Powell","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Hywel</i> ‘son of <i>Hywel</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘eminent’ (see   Howell  ).","Irish: mainly of Welsh origin as in 1 above, but sometimes a surname adopted as equivalent of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Phóil</b> ‘son of the servant of Saint Paul’ (see   Guilfoyle  ).","English: variant of   Paul   or   Poole  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Llewellyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."],"variants":[{"name":"Llywellyn","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."]},{"name":"Llywelyn","meanings":["(Welsh)  See  Llewelyn ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas ap Llewellyn Howell was born in 1340, in Monmouthshire, Wales, his father, Llewelyn ddu Black ap Owain, was 31 and his mother, Margaret verch Gwrwared, was 31. He married Elinor Verch Meredith in 1367, in Llanwern, Monmouthshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 14 August 1383, in his hometown, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1340–14 August 1383":"1340–14. august 1383","1340–1383":"1340–1383","1345–1370":"1345–1370","1367–1412":"1367–1412","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1412":"1412","1367":"1367","1345":"1345","1310":"1310","1340":"1340","1383":"1383","1370":"1370","14 August 1383":"14. august 1383","Llanwern, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Llanwern, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Maelor Saesneg, Flintshire, Wales":"Flintshire, Wales","Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouthshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1340–14 August 1383":"1340–14. elokuuta 1383","1340–1383":"1340–1383","1345–1370":"1345–1370","1367–1412":"1367–1412","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1310–Female":"1310–Kuollut","1412":"1412","1367":"1367","1345":"1345","1310":"1310","1340":"1340","1383":"1383","1370":"1370","14 August 1383":"14. elokuuta 1383","Llanwern, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Llanwern, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Maelor Saesneg, Flintshire, Wales":"Flintshire, Wales","Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouthshire, Wales"},"fr":{"1340–14 August 1383":"1340–14 août 1383","1340–1383":"1340–1383","1345–1370":"1345–1370","1367–1412":"1367–1412","1310–Male":"1310–Décédé","1310–Female":"1310–Décédée","1412":"1412","1367":"1367","1345":"1345","1310":"1310","1340":"1340","1383":"1383","1370":"1370","14 August 1383":"14 août 1383","Llanwern, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Llanwern, Monmouthshire, Galles","Wales":"Galles","Maelor Saesneg, Flintshire, Wales":"Flintshire, Galles","Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouthshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Thomas ap Llewellyn Howell est né en 1340, à Monmouthshire, Galles, son père, Llewelyn ddu Black ap Owain, avait 31 ans et sa mère, Margaret verch Gwrwared, avait 31 ans. Il a épousé Elinor Verch Meredith en 1367, à Llanwern, Monmouthshire, Galles. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Il est décédé le 14 août 1383, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 43 ans."},"de":{"134